Here is an example code for a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 with a single slash command `ban`:
```
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits } = require('discord.js');
const client = new Client({
  intents: [
    GatewayIntentBits.Guilds,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildMessages,
    GatewayIntentBits.GuildBans
  ]
});

client.commands = new Map();

client.commands.set('ban', {
  name: 'ban',
  description: 'Bans a member from the server',
  options: [
    {
      name: 'member',
      description: 'The member to ban',
      type: 'user',
      required: true
    }
  ],
  execute: async (interaction) => {
    const member = interaction.options.getUser('member');
    const guild = interaction.guild;
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason', true);

    if (!guild.me.permissions.has('BanMembers')) {
      return interaction.reply({ content: 'I don\'t have the permission to ban members.', ephemeral: true });
    }

    try {
      await guild.members.ban(member, { reason: reason });
      interaction.reply({ content: `Banned ${member.tag} from the server.` });
    } catch (error) {
      interaction.reply({ content: `Error banning ${member.tag}: ${error}`, ephemeral: true });
    }
  }
});

client.login('YOUR_BOT_TOKEN');

client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log('Bot is online!');
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  const command = client.commands.get(interaction.commandName);
  if (!command) return;

  try {
    await command.execute(interaction);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    interaction.reply({ content: 'There was an error while executing this command.', ephemeral: true });
  }
});
```
Here's an explanation of the code:

* We create a new Discord.js client instance and set up the intents for guilds, guild members, guild messages, and guild bans.
* We define a map to store our commands, and add a single command `ban` with options for the member to ban and an optional reason.
* The `execute` function is called when the `ban` command is invoked. It checks if the bot has the necessary permissions to ban members, and if not, returns an error message. It then bans the specified member and sends a success message.
* We set up the bot to login with our bot token.
* We set up event listeners for when the bot is ready and when an interaction (such as a slash command) is created.
* In the `interactionCreate` event listener, we check if the interaction is a command, and if so, execute the corresponding command.

Note that you'll need to replace `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN` with your actual bot token. You can obtain a bot token by creating a bot on the Discord Developer Portal and clicking on the "Token" button.

Here is an example of a high-quality testing framework in Cypress that utilizes Docker and captures screenshots:
```
// cypress/support/index.js
import { addMatchImageSnapshotCommand } from 'cypress-image-snapshot/command';
import { addStable } from '@cypress/stable';
import { Docker } from 'cypress-docker';

addMatchImageSnapshotCommand();
addStable();

// Set up Docker
const docker = new Docker();

// Define a custom command to run a Docker container
Cypress.Commands.add('dockerRun', (image, command) => {
  return docker.run(image, command);
});

// Define a custom command to capture a screenshot
Cypress.Commands.add('captureScreenshot', (name) => {
  return cy.get('body').screenshot(name, { capture: 'fullPage' });
});

// Define a custom command to compare screenshots
Cypress.Commands.add('compareScreenshot', (name, expected) => {
  return cy.get(`@${name}`).should('matchImageSnapshot', expected);
});

// Define a test suite
describe('My App', () => {
  beforeEach(() => {
    // Run the Docker container
    cy.dockerRun('my-app', 'npm start');
  });

  afterEach(() => {
    // Stop the Docker container
    cy.dockerStop();
  });

  it('should render the app', () => {
    // Visit the app
    cy.visit('http://localhost:3000');

    // Capture a screenshot
    cy.captureScreenshot('home-page');

    // Verify the screenshot matches the expected image
    cy.compareScreenshot('home-page', 'expected-home-page.png');
  });

  it('should render the login page', () => {
    // Visit the login page
    cy.visit('http://localhost:3000/login');

    // Capture a screenshot
    cy.captureScreenshot('login-page');

    // Verify the screenshot matches the expected image
    cy.compareScreenshot('login-page', 'expected-login-page.png');
  });
});
```
In this example, we:

1. Add the `addMatchImageSnapshotCommand` and `addStable` commands to enable image snapshotting and stable mode.
2. Set up a custom command `dockerRun` to run a Docker container.
3. Set up a custom command `captureScreenshot` to capture a screenshot of the page.
4. Set up a custom command `compareScreenshot` to compare the captured screenshot with an expected image.
5. Define a test suite with two tests:
	* The first test visits the app, captures a screenshot, and verifies that it matches the expected image.
	* The second test visits the login page, captures a screenshot, and verifies that it matches the expected image.

To run the tests, you'll need to:

1. Create a `Dockerfile` in the root of your project that builds your app.
2. Run `docker build -t my-app .` to build the Docker image.
3. Run `docker run -p 3000:3000 my-app` to start the Docker container.
4. Run `npx cypress run` to run the tests.

This will capture screenshots of each test and save them to the `cypress/screenshots` directory. You can then compare the captured screenshots with the expected images using the `compareScreenshot` command.

Note: Make sure to update the `expected-home-page.png` and `expected-login-page.png` files to match the expected screenshots of your app.

Here is a simple C++ function that uses the `std::regex` library to replace Markdown syntax with HTML:

```cpp
#include <regex>
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;

    // Headers
    html += "<h1>" + std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("^# (.*)"), "$1</h1>") + "</h1>";
    markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("^# (.*)"), "");

    // Bold and Italic
    html += std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("(\*([^\*]+)\*)|(_([^\_]+)_)", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript), "<strong>$2</strong>");
    markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("(\*([^\*]+)\*)|(_([^\_]+)_)", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript), "");

    // Links
    html += std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("(\[([^\]]+)\]\(([^)]+)\))", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript), "<a href=\"$3\">$2</a>");
    markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("(\[([^\]]+)\]\(([^)]+)\))", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript), "");

    // Lists
    html += std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("^(\*|\+|\- )(.*)$", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript), "<li>$2</li>");
    markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("^(\*|\+|\- )(.*)$", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript), "");

    // Code
    html += std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("``(.*)``", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript), "<code>$1</code>");
    markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex("``(.*)``", std::regex_constants::ECMAScript), "");

    return html;
}
```

This function replaces the following Markdown syntax with HTML:

- Headers: `# Heading` becomes `<h1>Heading</h1>`
- Bold and Italic: `*Bold*` or `_Italic_` becomes `<strong>Bold</strong>` or `<strong>Italic</strong>`
- Links: `[Link Text](http://www.example.com)` becomes `<a href="http://www.example.com">Link Text</a>`
- Lists: `- Item` becomes `<li>Item</li>`
- Code: ``Code`` becomes `<code>Code</code>`

Note that this is a very basic implementation and may not cover all possible Markdown syntax. You may need to add more regular expressions to handle more complex cases.

